To create a function that converts markdown to HTML, you'll need to handle the conversion rules for each markdown syntax element. This can be quite complex, especially when dealing with features like headers, lists, links, images, etc. For simplicity, let's implement a basic converter that supports headers, bold text, and inline links.

Here's an example of how you could write such a function in C++ using a simple approach:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::stringstream ss(markdown);
    std::string line;
    std::string html = "";

    while (std::getline(ss, line)) {
        if (line.empty()) {
            html += "<br />\n";
        } else if (line[0] == '#') {
            html += "<h2>";
            int level = 1;
            while (line[level] == '#') ++level;
            html += line.substr(1, level - 1);
            html += "</h2>\n";
        } else if (line.find('[') != std::string::npos && line.find(']') != std::string::npos && line.find('(') != std::string::npos && line.find(')') != std::string::npos) {
            size_t start_link = line.find("[");
            size_t end_link = line.find("]");
            size_t start_bracket = line.find("(");
            size_t end_bracket = line.find(")");

            std::string link_text = line.substr(start_link + 1, end_link - start_link - 1);
            std::string href = line.substr(start_bracket + 1, end_bracket - start_bracket - 1);

            html += "<a href=\"";
            html += href;
            html += "\">";
            html += link_text;
            html += "</a>";
        } else {
            // Simple conversion of inline bold text (Markdown does not support this natively)
            line = line.replace(line.find("**"), 2, "<strong>");
            line = line.replace(line.rfind("**") + 2, 2, "</strong>");

            html += line + "\n";
        }
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown_input = "## Hello, *world*! \n\n [Check out my website](https://example.com)";
    std::string converted_html = markdown_to_html(markdown_input);
    std::cout << converted_html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code snippet defines a function `markdown_to_html` that processes a string containing Markdown text and returns a corresponding string in HTML format. It supports headers (`#` followed by text), inline links (text `[link text]` between brackets and parentheses with the URL inside), and a basic implementation of bold text (surrounded by `**`). The `main` function demonstrates how to use this function with a sample input string.

Keep in mind that this is a very simplified example and does not cover all possible Markdown features, such as lists, images, code blocks, etc. For more complex Markdown to HTML conversion, consider using specialized libraries like `pandoc`, or exploring existing open-source projects like `cmark-github` or `libmarkdown`.

