To create a table of contents (TOC) that automatically updates based on your headings in LaTeX, you need to include the `tableofcontents` command in your document's structure. Below is a simple example demonstrating how this is done. 

Here's the code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% The next line is important to enable TOC functionality
\usepackage{tocbibind}

\title{Example Document with Automatic Table of Contents}
\author{John Doe}
\date{\today} % Automatically uses today's date

\begin{document}

\maketitle % Generates the title page using the details provided above

\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents

\section{Introduction}
This section introduces the topic and sets the stage for the following sections.

\subsection{Brief Overview}
A brief overview of what will be covered in this document.

\section{Main Content}
Here we discuss the main content in detail.

\subsection{Detail 1}
Explores detail 1 in depth.

\subsection{Detail 2}
Explores detail 2 in depth.

\section{Conclusion}
Summarizes the main points and offers final thoughts.

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **`\documentclass{article}`**: This line specifies that you are creating an article-style document.
- **`\usepackage{tocbibind}`**: This package is used here as an example, but it's not necessary for basic TOC functionality. Normally, you might just use `\usepackage{tocloft}` or `\usepackage{hyperref}` for more advanced features.
- **`\title{}`, `\author{}`, `\date{}`**: These commands define the title, author, and date of the document respectively.
- **`\maketitle`**: After defining the title, author, and date, this command creates the title page.
- **`\tableofcontents`**: This command automatically generates a table of contents at the specified location in the document. It looks for `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc., commands and organizes them into a TOC.
- **`\section{}`, `\subsection{}`**: These commands create headers that are recognized by the TOC generator to organize content appropriately.

The TOC will update dynamically if you add, remove, or rename these sections, making it a powerful tool for organizing documents with many sections.

To display a chessboard using LaTeX, we can create a TikZ picture where each square is represented by a node. Here's an example of how to do it:

First, you need to include the necessary packages in your LaTeX document preamble:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{positioning, decorations.pathreplacing}

% Define styles for light and dark squares
\tikzset{
  lightSquare/.style={fill=lightgray},
  darkSquare/.style={fill=gray!30}
}

% Define the size of the chessboard
\def\chessboardSize{8}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    % Draw the chessboard with appropriate colors
    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5, transform shape]
        % Draw rows and columns
        \foreach \i in {1,...,\chessboardSize} {
            \foreach \j in {1,...,\chessboardSize} {
                % Alternating light/dark squares
                \ifodd{\i+\j}
                    \node[lightSquare, minimum size=2cm] at (\j,-\i) {};
                \else
                    \node[darkSquare, minimum size=2cm] at (\j,-\i) {};
                \fi
            }
        }
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{Chessboard}
    \label{fig:chessboard}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX code defines a chessboard with the `tikz` package, which is used for creating graphics. It uses the `positioning` and `decorations.pathreplacing` libraries for convenience. The `lightSquare` and `darkSquare` styles are defined for coloring the squares, and the `scale` parameter allows adjusting the size of the chessboard. The `minimum size` is set to 2cm here, but you can change it as needed.

The `for each` loops create the rows and columns, and the condition `ifodd` alternates between light and dark squares based on the sum of the current row and column indices.

You can compile this LaTeX code to generate an image of a chessboard, which will be included in your document as Figure 1 (labeled as `\ref{fig:chessboard}`).

